The problem is that changing time windows (e.g. hitting the "history" API) on low-power virtual servers 
exhausts the CPU and causes Kula to drop metrics. This is because Kula's time-series storage uses 
a JSON file ring buffer, and ReadRange decodes every single historical record from the underlying tier 
(which could be gigabytes of JSON, tens of thousands of records) fully into memory using json.Unmarshal 
before checking if the timestamp even falls within the requested query range.

By extracting the timestamp using a fast string match bytes.Index before fully unmarshaling the JSON, 
we bypass 99% of the computational overhead, solving CPU exhaustion on 1-2 vCPU instances.
</model>

